[2]
Date: 1 Feb 2007
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: El Mundo, Bolivia [translated by Mod.JGM; edited]
<http://www.elmundo.com.bo/Secundarianew.asp?edicion=28/01/2007&Tipo=Economia&Cod=6344>

Ten cattle on a farm belonging to a Mennonite individual in Cuatro Canadas
municipality, field No. 211, were reported to have foot-and-mouth disease
(FMD), constituting an outbreak. There are 4 additional animals under
observation, and this generated an alert for animal breeders. The local
union of cattle farmers immediately reported this occurrence to the
National Council for Foot-and-Mouth Disease Eradication and the Santa Cruz
Prefecture, in order to control the outbreak and take measures in order not
to harm the process of certification at the International Epizootic
Organization (OIE, according to its Spanish initials), since Bolivia
intends to widen its meat and dairy product exporting business.
Mr. George Prestel, head of FEGASACRUZ (Santa Cruz Farmers Union), stated
yesterday morning that they met with representatives of the National
Commission and Prefecture, in order to request the Ministry of Agriculture
issue an Urgency Decree in order to get financial resources for a
vaccination campaign against the disease, which is affecting local farmers.
In addition to looking for responsible persons, Mr. Prestel explained that
first of all an exhaustive analysis will be performed in order to determine
the origin of the reemergence of FMD in that particular farm, and later to
control this focus, so that responsibility for the outbreak can be determined.
"The outbreak was confirmed by laboratory tests, and samples have been sent
to PANAFTOSA (WHO/PAHO PanAmerican Center for FMD) for certification", said
Mr. Prestel, and he pointed out that there are 4 more cattle under
observation, in addition to the animals that might have come into contact
with affected cattle.
An officer from the National Service for Agricultural Sanitation and Food
Safety (SENSAG, according to its Spanish initials) said that this
reemergent outbreak will lead to economic loss, "so we have to act as soon
as possible so that the harmful effects are minimized." He also said that
as a preventive measure to halt disease spread in cattle, a ban was
implemented in field No. 211 in Cuatro Canadas municipality and the
surrounding areas, where no movement of animals will be allowed, and every
animal movement in Cuatro Canadas and Pailon municipalities will be
controlled by SENASAG.
Some other additional measures will also be implemented, depending on the
results of tests to be performed in the next few days, "in order to
determine the true origin of this FMD outbreak and to identify the animals
that had been in contact with affected cattle".
Mr. Prestel emphasized that technical analyses will be performed in order
to determine the origin of this outbreak, so that the occurrence can be
controlled in order to minimize losses, and "naturally, discussions will be
held to determine responsibility." He also pointed out that for 2 years
they have been demanding that SENASAG personnel be kept in their jobs,
since the continuous change in such personnel affected the safety of
vaccination campaigns performed since 2001.
Paraguay decreed a sanitary alert last Saturday because of the said FMD
outbreak in a farm in Santa Cruz de la Sierra Province in Bolivia.
Mr. Hugo Corrales, head of the Animal health Service, declared to the press
that "4 calves have FMD in a farm located 370 kilometers from the
Paraguayan Chaco border".
The border with Santa Cruz (Bolivia) is 900 kilometers west of Asuncion,
the Capital City of Paraguay.
"This alert means that no Bolivian cattle should enter Paraguay, since this
latter country is free of FMD because of vaccination", he pointed out.
"We hope that Bolivian sanitary authorities have taken preventive measures
to stop spread of the disease and that they reported this to MERCOSUR
(South American Economic Community)", said Mr. Corrales.
In 2006, Paraguay sold 450 million U.S. dollars worth of meat products to
the U.S., Chile, Europe, Russia, and Asia. The local markets even ran out
of stock, so that supermarket owners had to import meat products in order
to satisfy the local demand.
